The reason that your regular expression does not work is that it matches any `/` in the URI that is not followed by `api`. So `/api` and `/api/api` will not be denied, but `/foo` and `/api/foo` will be.

It is easily fixed by adding an anchor (`^`) to the beginning of the regular expression:

    location ~ ^/(?!api).* { ... }

---
An alternative approach uses prefix locations:

    location / {
        deny all;
    }

    location /api {
        try_files $uri $uri/ /index.php?$query_string;
    }

    location ~ \.php$ {
        internal;

        ...
    }

The `internal` directive prevents direct access to URIs ending with `.php`. See [this document](http://nginx.org/en/docs/http/ngx_http_core_module.html#internal) for details.

