[stackblitz simple example](https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-gxc114)

From [Angular docs on Date pipe](https://angular.io/api/common/DatePipe)


Format examples
These examples transform a date into various formats,
**assuming that dateObj is a JavaScript Date object** for year: 2015, month: 6, day: 15, hour: 21, minute: 43, second: 11, given in the local time for the en-US locale.

```
{{ dateObj | date }}               // output is &#39;Jun 15, 2015&#39;
{{ dateObj | date:&#39;medium&#39; }}      // output is &#39;Jun 15, 2015, 9:43:11 PM&#39;
{{ dateObj | date:&#39;shortTime&#39; }}   // output is &#39;9:43 PM&#39;
{{ dateObj | date:&#39;mm:ss&#39; }}       // output is &#39;43:11&#39;
```

From [MDN on JavaScript Date Object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Date)
```
var date1 = new Date(&#39;December 17, 1995 03:24:00&#39;);
// Sun Dec 17 1995 03:24:00 GMT...

var date2 = new Date(&#39;1995-12-17T03:24:00&#39;);
// Sun Dec 17 1995 03:24:00 GMT...
```

Convert your date as follows before sending it to DatePipe. Safari, won&#39;t support this kind of date format: &#39;2014-02-18 15:00:48&#39;, **you should change the space to T.** 

`&#39;2014-02-18 15:00:48&#39;.replace(/\s/, &#39;T&#39;)`

     &lt;div class=&quot;date-text&quot; nz-col nzSpan=&quot;24&quot;&gt;
        {{ validDateFormat(dayWeather.date) | date: &#39;EEEE&#39; }}
     &lt;/div&gt;


In your component.ts, create a method to convert the space to T as follows:

    validDateFormat(dateString) {
      if(dateString) {
        return dateString.replace(/\s/, &#39;T&#39;);
      }

      return null;
      
